238
00:19:10,962 --> 00:19:12,088
Uh-huh.

239
00:19:12,255 --> 00:19:16,050
Detective, the room was
security locked. No one came or went.

240
00:19:16,217 --> 00:19:20,221
You saw that yourself. Doesn't
that mean this has to be suicide?

241
00:19:20,471 --> 00:19:22,056
Yep.

242
00:19:22,932 --> 00:19:25,643
Unless the killer's still in here.

243
00:19:28,271 --> 00:19:31,608
You're joking, right? This is ridiculous.

244
00:19:31,774 --> 00:19:35,987
Yeah, I know. The Three Laws,
your perfect circle of protection.

245
00:19:36,487 --> 00:19:40,658
A robot cannot harm a human being.
The first law of robotics.

246
00:19:40,825 --> 00:19:45,663
Yes, I've seen your commercials. But the
second law states a robot must obey...

247
00:19:45,914 --> 00:19:49,667
...any order given by a human being.
What if it was told to kill?

248
00:19:49,918 --> 00:19:52,670
Impossible. It would conflict
with the first law.

249
00:19:52,837 --> 00:19:56,007
Right, but the third law states a robot can defend itself.

250
00:19:56,257 --> 00:20:00,595
Only when that action does not conflict
with the first or second laws.

251
00:20:00,762 --> 00:20:04,015
You know what they say, laws are made to be broken.

252
00:20:04,182 --> 00:20:07,310
No, not these laws.
They're hardwired into every robot.

253
00:20:07,727 --> 00:20:11,481
A robot could no more commit murder
than a human could walk on water.

254
00:20:11,648 --> 00:20:15,318
You know, there was this one guy a long time ago.

255
00:20:26,371 --> 00:20:28,665
- Stay back!
- Calm down, detective.

256
00:20:29,374 --> 00:20:32,377
The only thing dangerous in this room is you.

257
00:20:32,543 --> 00:20:35,046
Deactivate.

258
00:20:36,172 --> 00:20:37,590
Look, it's fine.

259
00:20:38,049 --> 00:20:42,804
You're looking at the result of clever
programming. An imitation of free will.

260
00:20:42,971 --> 00:20:45,473
Let's do an imitation of protecting our asses.

261
00:20:45,640 --> 00:20:47,767
CALVIN:
Don't be absurd.

262
00:20:48,184 --> 00:20:50,395
You were startled by a jack-in-the-box.

263
00:20:50,979 --> 00:20:52,981
- Deactivate!
- Let him go.

264
00:20:53,147 --> 00:20:55,900
It's not going to hurt us.
I gave you an order!

265
00:20:56,067 --> 00:20:59,237
- He's not listening right now, lady.
- V.I.K.I., seal the lab!

266
00:20:59,404 --> 00:21:00,905
No, V.I.K.I., leave the...

267
00:21:01,990 --> 00:21:03,908
V.I.K.I.: (ON SPEAKER)
Command confirmed.

268
00:21:04,492 --> 00:21:05,660
(SPOONER GRUNTING)

269
00:21:22,468 --> 00:21:24,053
(CROWD GASPING)

270
00:21:28,182 --> 00:21:29,517
SPOONER:
Police!

271
00:22:02,467 --> 00:22:05,970
- You've hurt it. Badly.
- Where's it going?

272
00:22:06,304 --> 00:22:09,307
- Where?
- It needs to repair itself.

273
00:22:11,142 --> 00:22:13,936
- John, I need backup.
- You don't need backup.

274
00:22:14,103 --> 00:22:15,313
That's nobody.

275
00:22:15,480 --> 00:22:17,148
- What are you doing?
- Driving.

276
00:22:17,315 --> 00:22:19,484
- By hand?
- Do you see me on the phone?

277
00:22:19,650 --> 00:22:23,946
- Not at these speeds.
- John, please, just send the backup.

278
00:22:24,113 --> 00:22:27,784
Try to listen, detective.
That robot is not going to harm us.

279
00:22:28,076 --> 00:22:29,911
There must have been unknown factors...

280
00:22:30,078 --> 00:22:32,955
...but somehow acting as it did kept us out of harm.

281
00:22:33,122 --> 00:22:36,376
<i>- A robot cannot endanger a human.
WOMAN: (ON SPEAKER) Alert.</i>

282
00:22:37,919 --> 00:22:41,255
Ah! Asshole!

283
00:22:41,798 --> 00:22:44,467
Which is more than I can say for you.

284
00:22:44,759 --> 00:22:48,262
It was a left, by the way. Back there.

285
00:22:49,138 --> 00:22:51,099
You must know my ex-wife.

286
00:23:00,691 --> 00:23:02,360
SPOONER:
So where is everybody?

287
00:23:02,527 --> 00:23:06,072
This facility was designed,
built and is operated mechanically.

288
00:23:06,239 --> 00:23:09,951
No significant human presence
from inception to production.

289
00:23:10,493 --> 00:23:13,704
<i>- So robots building robots.
WOMAN: (ON SPEAKER) Code, please.</i>

290
00:23:13,913 --> 00:23:15,123
That's just stupid.

291
00:23:15,540 --> 00:23:17,458
I'll get the inventory specs.

292
00:23:17,875 --> 00:23:20,586
Our daily finishing capacity
is 1000 NS-5s.

293
00:23:21,087 --> 00:23:22,713
I'm showing...

294
00:23:23,214 --> 00:23:25,091
...1001.

295
00:23:41,399 --> 00:23:44,277
Attention, NS-5s.

296
00:23:46,362 --> 00:23:48,739
Well, you're the robot shrink.

297
00:23:51,909 --> 00:23:55,621
CALVIN: There is a robot
in this formation that does not belong.

298
00:23:55,955 --> 00:23:57,331
Identify it.

299
00:23:57,748 --> 00:23:59,000
One of us.

300
00:23:59,167 --> 00:24:02,086
- Which one?
NS-5 ROBOTS: One of us.

301
00:24:02,628 --> 00:24:04,589
How much did you say these cost?

302
00:24:04,755 --> 00:24:07,967
These NS-5s haven't been configured.
They're just hardware.

303
00:24:08,259 --> 00:24:10,845
Basic Three Laws operating system.
That's it.

304
00:24:11,012 --> 00:24:14,932
- They don't know any better.
- Well, what would you suggest?

305
00:24:15,141 --> 00:24:19,437
Interview each one, cross-reference
their responses to detect anomalies.

306
00:24:19,937 --> 00:24:23,024
- How long would that take?
- About three weeks.

307
00:24:23,191 --> 00:24:25,943
Okay. Go ahead and get started.

308
00:24:29,280 --> 00:24:30,698
Robots...

309
00:24:31,032 --> 00:24:33,784
...you will not move. Confirm command.

310
00:24:33,993 --> 00:24:35,203
Command confirmed.

311
00:24:36,996 --> 00:24:38,789
CALVIN:
Detective, what are you doing?

312
00:24:38,956 --> 00:24:41,292
They're programmed with the Three Laws.

313
00:24:41,542 --> 00:24:46,797
We have 1000 robots that won't protect
themselves if it violates orders...

314
00:24:46,964 --> 00:24:49,050
...and I'm betting, one who will.

315
00:24:49,217 --> 00:24:52,803
- Put your gun down.
- Why do you give them faces?

316
00:24:52,970 --> 00:24:55,473
Try to friendly them up, make them look human.

317
00:24:55,765 --> 00:24:57,767
These robots cannot be intimidated.

318
00:24:58,142 --> 00:25:01,771
- If you didn't, we wouldn't trust them.
- These are USR property.

319
00:25:01,979 --> 00:25:06,275
Not me. These things are just lights
and clockwork.

320
00:25:06,651 --> 00:25:08,611
(CALVIN GASPING)

321
00:25:08,778 --> 00:25:10,488
CALVIN:
Are you crazy?!

322
00:25:11,030 --> 00:25:12,657
SPOONER: Let me ask you something, doc.

323
00:25:12,990 --> 00:25:16,577
Does thinking you're the last sane man
on earth make you crazy?

324
00:25:16,744 --> 00:25:20,206
Because if it does, maybe I am.

325
00:25:24,544 --> 00:25:26,712
SPOONER: Gotcha. Get the hell out of here!

326
00:25:44,605 --> 00:25:45,773
Detective!

327
00:26:03,040 --> 00:26:05,793
(SCREAMING AND GROANING)

328
00:26:08,963 --> 00:26:10,548
SONNY: What am I?

329
00:26:10,715 --> 00:26:13,259
NS-5 ROBOTS:
Can I help you, sir? Can I help you, sir?

330
00:26:19,015 --> 00:26:21,142
MAN #1: There he is!
MAN #2: Stand where you are!

331
00:26:21,309 --> 00:26:23,603
Deactivate at once!

332
00:26:24,395 --> 00:26:27,356
Obey the command! Deactivate!

333
00:26:27,607 --> 00:26:29,692
MAN #3: Don't move!
COMMANDER: Open fire!

334
00:26:46,709 --> 00:26:47,918
Hold your fire!

335
00:26:48,085 --> 00:26:49,462
MAN #4: Easy.
MAN #5: He's down.

336
00:26:49,629 --> 00:26:51,505
COMMANDER:
All units, stand down!

337
00:26:51,672 --> 00:26:54,884
<i>MAN: (OVER RADIO)
Central, please be advised, we're code four.</i>

338
00:26:55,051 --> 00:26:58,429
<i>Code four, NS-5 is in custody.
NS-5 in custody.</i>

339
00:27:00,431 --> 00:27:03,434
SPOONER: You have no idea
what I went through to clip this thing.

340
00:27:03,601 --> 00:27:05,811
You think you brought me something good.

341
00:27:05,978 --> 00:27:08,814
- That thing did it!
- Keep your voice down. Did what?

342
00:27:08,981 --> 00:27:11,108
We have a suicide. End of story.

343
00:27:11,484 --> 00:27:14,862
- I am telling you, that robot killed him!
- That's impossible.

344
00:27:15,029 --> 00:27:19,200
And if it is possible, it better be
in somebody else's precinct.

345
00:27:19,408 --> 00:27:21,577
John, give me five minutes with it.

346
00:27:21,744 --> 00:27:23,788
Are you nuts? I talked to the DA.

347
00:27:23,954 --> 00:27:27,500
Nobody goes in there until Robertson
and his attorneys get here.

348
00:27:27,667 --> 00:27:30,628
- This is my suspect!
- It's a can opener!

349
00:27:30,920 --> 00:27:35,633
John, don't do this to me.
I am asking you for five minutes.

350
00:27:36,258 --> 00:27:38,219
What if I'm right?

351
00:27:45,851 --> 00:27:48,729
Well, then I guess we're gonna miss the good old days.

352
00:27:48,896 --> 00:27:50,231
What good old days?

353
00:27:50,981 --> 00:27:53,651
When people were killed by other people.

354
00:28:00,991 --> 00:28:02,535
Five minutes.

355
00:28:30,646 --> 00:28:34,859
SPOONER: Murder's a new trick
for a robot. Congratulations.

356
00:28:37,194 --> 00:28:38,446
Respond.

357
00:28:41,198 --> 00:28:43,909
SONNY: What does this action signify?

358
00:28:45,077 --> 00:28:48,414
As you entered, when you looked at the other human.

359
00:28:48,581 --> 00:28:50,875
What does it mean?

360
00:28:52,585 --> 00:28:56,088
SPOONER: It's a sign of trust. A human thing.
You wouldn't understand.

361
00:28:57,548 --> 00:29:00,801
SONNY: My father tried to teach me human emotions.

362
00:29:00,968 --> 00:29:02,553
They are...

363
00:29:02,720 --> 00:29:04,346
...difficult.

364
00:29:04,513 --> 00:29:06,849
SPOONER: You mean your designer.

365
00:29:07,850 --> 00:29:09,143
SONNY: Yes.

366
00:29:11,270 --> 00:29:13,314
SPOONER: So why'd you murder him?

367
00:29:14,774 --> 00:29:17,026
SONNY: I did not murder Dr. Lanning.

368
00:29:17,193 --> 00:29:20,029
Wanna explain why you were hiding at the crime scene?

369
00:29:20,196 --> 00:29:22,448
SONNY: I was frightened.

370
00:29:23,157 --> 00:29:27,578
SPOONER: Robots don't feel fear.
They don't feel anything.

371
00:29:27,745 --> 00:29:31,248
- They don't get hungry, they don't sleep.
- I do.

372
00:29:32,082 --> 00:29:34,251
SONNY: I have even had dreams.

373
00:29:34,960 --> 00:29:39,173
SPOONER: Human beings have dreams.
Even dogs have dreams. But not you.

374
00:29:39,340 --> 00:29:43,135
SONNY: You are just a machine.
An imitation of life.

375
00:29:45,054 --> 00:29:47,473
SPOONER: Can a robot write a symphony?

376
00:29:47,640 --> 00:29:51,477
Can a robot turn a canvas into a beautiful masterpiece?

377
00:29:52,394 --> 00:29:54,146
SONNY: Can you?

378
00:30:00,402 --> 00:30:04,323
SPOONER: You murdered him because he was
teaching you to simulate emotions...

379
00:30:04,490 --> 00:30:06,784
...and things got out of control.

380
00:30:06,951 --> 00:30:08,869
SONNY: I did not murder him.

381
00:30:09,036 --> 00:30:12,540
SPOONER: But emotions don't seem like
a useful simulation for a robot.

382
00:30:12,706 --> 00:30:14,625
SONNY: I did not murder him.

383
00:30:14,875 --> 00:30:18,504
SPOONER: I don't want my toaster or vacuum
cleaner appearing emotional.

384
00:30:19,255 --> 00:30:21,257
SONNY: I did not murder him!

385
00:30:34,103 --> 00:30:36,272
SPOONER: That one's called anger.

386
00:30:36,856 --> 00:30:38,524
Ever simulate anger before?

387
00:30:40,985 --> 00:30:42,945
Answer me, canner!

388
00:30:44,321 --> 00:30:46,073
SONNY: My name is Sonny.

389
00:30:48,492 --> 00:30:50,995
SPOONER: So we're naming you now.

390
00:30:52,121 --> 00:30:56,250
That why you murdered him?
He made you angry?

391
00:30:56,417 --> 00:30:58,669
SONNY: Dr. Lanning killed himself.

392
00:31:00,129 --> 00:31:03,674
I don't know why he wanted to die.

393
00:31:05,009 --> 00:31:07,011
I thought he was happy.

394
00:31:09,597 --> 00:31:11,765
Maybe it was something I did.

395
00:31:12,808 --> 00:31:14,602
Did I do something?

396
00:31:16,520 --> 00:31:19,523
He asked me for a favor.
Made me promise.

397
00:31:19,690 --> 00:31:22,776
- What favor?
- Maybe I was wrong.

398
00:31:22,943 --> 00:31:24,653
Maybe he was scared.

399
00:31:24,862 --> 00:31:27,781
What are you talking about?
Scared of what?

400
00:31:28,616 --> 00:31:32,536
You have to do what someone asks you,
don't you, Detective Spooner?

401
00:31:32,745 --> 00:31:35,956
- How the hell did you know my name?
- Don't you...

402
00:31:36,415 --> 00:31:38,876
...if you love them?

403
00:31:47,593 --> 00:31:50,596
My robots don't kill people, Lieutenant Bergin.

404
00:31:50,763 --> 00:31:52,932
My attorneys filed a brief with the DA.

405
00:31:53,098 --> 00:31:56,352
He assures me a robot cannot be charged with homicide.

406
00:31:56,685 --> 00:32:00,856
The brief confirms murder can only be
committed when one human kills another.

407
00:32:01,065 --> 00:32:05,903
Detective, you're not suggesting
this robot be treated as human, are you?

408
00:32:06,570 --> 00:32:09,865
Granted, we can't rule out the robot's proximity...

409
00:32:10,074 --> 00:32:14,078
...to the death of Dr. Lanning.
Having said that, it's a machine.

410
00:32:14,578 --> 00:32:16,246
It's the property of USR.

411
00:32:16,413 --> 00:32:20,834
At worst, that places this incident within
the realm of an industrial accident.

412
00:32:21,001 --> 00:32:23,295
As a matter of course, faulty machinery...

413
00:32:23,462 --> 00:32:26,966
...will be returned to USR
for diagnostics, then decommissioned.

414
00:32:30,010 --> 00:32:33,472
This is a gag order.
Anyone here so much as hinting...

415
00:32:33,639 --> 00:32:37,476
...at the possibility of a killer robot being apprehended...

416
00:32:37,643 --> 00:32:40,312
...will be deemed to be inciting irrational panic.

417
00:32:40,521 --> 00:32:43,565
You'll be subject to the full penalty of law.

418
00:32:43,732 --> 00:32:46,610
To hell with this guy.
Don't let him take this robot.

419
00:32:46,902 --> 00:32:48,237
We got nothing.

420
00:32:48,404 --> 00:32:52,282
- This is political bullshit. Call the mayor!
ROBERTSON: Lieutenant Bergin...

421
00:32:52,449 --> 00:32:54,410
...His Honor, the mayor.

422
00:33:03,502 --> 00:33:04,712
BERGIN:
Yes, sir.

423
00:33:25,149 --> 00:33:26,775
(MAN LAUGHING)

424
00:33:29,695 --> 00:33:33,782
<i>In a bizarre turn, the rollout of USR's
new generation of robots...</i>

425
00:33:33,949 --> 00:33:36,452
<i>...was marred by the death of Alfred Lanning...</i>

426
00:33:36,660 --> 00:33:39,788
<i>...cofounder of the company
and designer of the NS-5.</i>

427
00:33:39,955 --> 00:33:43,333
<i>Dr. Lanning died this morning
at USR headquarters.</i>

428
00:33:43,667 --> 00:33:46,336
<i>The cause of death is an apparent suicide.</i>

429
00:33:46,670 --> 00:33:49,298
NS-4 COUNTERMAN:
Your second round, sir.

430
00:33:49,673 --> 00:33:50,883
Thank you.

431
00:33:51,050 --> 00:33:55,554
<i>He founded U.S. Robotics Inc.
With Lawrence Robertson in 2020...</i>

432
00:33:55,721 --> 00:33:59,016
<i>...and launched
the Nestor Class 1 robot....</i>

433
00:33:59,183 --> 00:34:02,644
<i>I was just thinking, this thing is just like The Wolf Man.</i>

434
00:34:02,811 --> 00:34:06,982
- Uh-oh. I'm really scared right now.
- No.

435
00:34:07,191 --> 00:34:10,152
Listen. Guy creates monster.

436
00:34:10,319 --> 00:34:13,989
<i>Monster kills guy.
Everybody kills monster. Wolf Man.</i>

437
00:34:14,490 --> 00:34:16,283
<i>That's Frankenstein.</i>

438
00:34:16,867 --> 00:34:21,205
<i>Frankenstein, Wolf Man, Dracula...
Shit, it's over. Case closed.</i>

439
00:34:21,371 --> 00:34:24,875
<i>...had a dream of a robot in
every household. And the NS-5....</i>

440
00:34:25,042 --> 00:34:26,877
So why the look?

441
00:34:27,461 --> 00:34:29,004
What look?

442
00:34:29,213 --> 00:34:32,299
- That look.
- This is my face. It's not a look.

443
00:34:32,633 --> 00:34:35,636
Good. Good, no look is great.

444
00:34:36,637 --> 00:34:37,846
Only...

445
00:34:38,013 --> 00:34:40,724
...he was really quick to want to destroy it.

446
00:34:40,891 --> 00:34:45,395
What should he do? Put a hat on it and
stand it on Michigan Avenue? Let it go.

447
00:34:45,562 --> 00:34:47,898
What was the motive, John?

448
00:34:49,233 --> 00:34:53,362
Brother, it's a robot. It doesn't need
a motive. It just has to be broken.

449
00:34:53,862 --> 00:34:56,740
This thing looked like it needed a motive.

450
00:34:57,241 --> 00:35:00,202
- It could have killed me. Why didn't it?
- That's it.

451
00:35:00,369 --> 00:35:02,454
You want me to call your grandmother?

452
00:35:02,621 --> 00:35:04,623
Because I will, you know.

453
00:35:05,624 --> 00:35:07,251
Yeah, I didn't think so.

454
00:35:07,543 --> 00:35:10,129
Look, you were actually right, for once.

455
00:35:10,295 --> 00:35:13,882
You're living proof that it's better
to be lucky than smart.

456
00:35:14,299 --> 00:35:15,884
(BERGIN CHUCKLES)

457
00:35:16,051 --> 00:35:19,888
Come on. To the right guy
for the right job.

458
00:35:22,349 --> 00:35:24,643
- What'd you say?
- Now what?

459
00:35:24,810 --> 00:35:26,854
Come on, I'm giving you a compliment.

460
00:35:27,271 --> 00:35:30,399
With the rocks you been looking under
to find a bad robot...

461
00:35:30,566 --> 00:35:32,818
...what are the odds you'd be the guy to find one?

462
00:35:32,985 --> 00:35:34,153
Hmm.

463
00:35:34,319 --> 00:35:37,739
I wasn't just the right guy for the job.
I was the perfect guy.

464
00:35:37,906 --> 00:35:39,533
Damn right.

465
00:35:39,700 --> 00:35:42,369
What if I was supposed to go for that robot?

466
00:35:42,578 --> 00:35:44,580
Come on, don't do this to yourself.

467
00:35:44,788 --> 00:35:47,791
The robot said that Lanning was scared.
Scared of what?

468
00:35:48,375 --> 00:35:51,086
I need a rain check. Let me get this.

469
00:35:52,796 --> 00:35:55,799
<i>WOMAN: (ON SCANNER) Total: $46.50.
- Spoon!</i>

470
00:35:58,427 --> 00:35:59,803
Nice shoes.

471
00:36:51,230 --> 00:36:52,272
(BEEPING)

472
00:36:52,439 --> 00:36:53,482
Identify.

473
00:36:54,066 --> 00:36:57,569
<i>DEMOLITION ROBOT:
USR demolition robot, series 9-4.</i>

474
00:36:57,861 --> 00:37:00,739
<i>Demolition scheduled for 8 a.m.
tomorrow.</i>

475
00:37:01,156 --> 00:37:02,366
<i>Authorization.</i>

476
00:37:02,658 --> 00:37:05,577
<i>DEMOLITION ROBOT:
Deed owner, U.S. Robotics Corporation.</i>

477
00:37:05,744 --> 00:37:06,995
<i>Lawrence Robertson, CEO.</i>

478
00:37:22,427 --> 00:37:23,512
<i>LANNING: (ON SCANNER)
Welcome.</i>

479
00:37:27,766 --> 00:37:31,436
(WIND HOWLING)

480
00:37:48,203 --> 00:37:50,038
What you looking for, Spoon?

481
00:38:06,805 --> 00:38:08,974
(DOOR CREAKING)

482
00:38:42,966 --> 00:38:44,593
Run last program.

483
00:38:45,510 --> 00:38:47,846
<i>LANNING:
Ever since the first computers...</i>

484
00:38:48,555 --> 00:38:51,266
<i>...there have always been ghosts in the machine.</i>

485
00:38:52,100 --> 00:38:55,062
<i>Random segments of code that have grouped together...</i>

486
00:38:55,228 --> 00:38:58,106
<i>...to form unexpected protocols.</i>

487
00:38:58,732 --> 00:39:01,068
<i>What might be called behavior.</i>

488
00:39:01,234 --> 00:39:04,488
<i>Unanticipated, these free radicals...</i>

489
00:39:04,654 --> 00:39:06,948
<i>...engender questions of free will...</i>

490
00:39:07,240 --> 00:39:11,495
<i>...creativity and even the nature
of what we might call the soul.</i>

491
00:39:12,746 --> 00:39:17,417
<i>What happens in a robot's brain
when it ceases to be useful?</i>

492
00:39:18,377 --> 00:39:19,628
Shit!

493
00:39:20,295 --> 00:39:23,006
<i>Why is it that robots stored in an empty space...</i>

494
00:39:23,173 --> 00:39:24,591
Beat it.

495
00:39:24,758 --> 00:39:27,636
<i>...will seek out each other rather than stand alone?</i>

496
00:39:29,930 --> 00:39:32,641
<i>How do we explain this behavior?</i>

497
00:39:32,849 --> 00:39:36,269
(WHIRRING)

498
00:39:45,112 --> 00:39:49,199
(BELL JINGLING)

499
00:39:49,366 --> 00:39:50,784
(MEOWS)

500
00:39:51,034 --> 00:39:55,497
Look, I understand you've experienced
a loss, but this relationship can't work.

501
00:39:55,664 --> 00:39:59,376
You're a cat, I'm black, and I'm not gonna be hurt again.

502
00:39:59,543 --> 00:40:02,671
(CLANGING AND RUMBLING)

503
00:40:03,547 --> 00:40:06,299
(SHOUTING AND GROANING)

504
00:40:11,221 --> 00:40:12,556
(MEOWING)

505
00:40:16,351 --> 00:40:18,854
(SCREAMING)

506
00:40:44,963 --> 00:40:47,799
(MEOWING)

507
00:40:59,811 --> 00:41:02,439
(GRUNTING)

508
00:41:09,738 --> 00:41:13,325
(MEOWING)

509
00:41:21,166 --> 00:41:22,709
(KNOCKING)

510
00:41:24,836 --> 00:41:28,673
What happened to you?
Do you ever have a normal day?

511
00:41:29,174 --> 00:41:31,009
Yeah, once.

512
00:41:31,176 --> 00:41:33,011
It was a Thursday.

513
00:41:33,220 --> 00:41:35,430
Is there something I can help you with?

514
00:41:35,639 --> 00:41:38,099
- Hey, do you like cats?
- What?

515
00:41:38,266 --> 00:41:40,435
Cats. Do you like them?

516
00:41:40,685 --> 00:41:42,437
No. I'm allergic.

517
00:41:42,646 --> 00:41:44,397
You're saying cats did this to you?

518
00:41:44,981 --> 00:41:47,943
How the hell would cats do this to me?
Are you crazy?

519
00:41:50,320 --> 00:41:51,988
Why are we talking about cats?

520
00:41:52,280 --> 00:41:55,784
Because I have a cat in my trunk, and he's homeless.

521
00:41:56,743 --> 00:41:59,663
Detective, are you going to tell me what's going on?

522
00:42:00,163 --> 00:42:04,960
It's actually probably my fault.
I'm like a malfunction magnet.

523
00:42:05,168 --> 00:42:08,171
Because your shit keeps malfunctioning around me.

524
00:42:08,463 --> 00:42:10,799
A demo bot tore through Lanning's house...

525
00:42:11,216 --> 00:42:13,134
...with me still inside.

526
00:42:13,301 --> 00:42:15,178
CALVIN:
That's highly improbable.

527
00:42:15,470 --> 00:42:17,180
SPOONER:
Yeah, I'm sure it is.

528
00:42:17,889 --> 00:42:19,432
(GROANING)

529
00:42:22,269 --> 00:42:25,021
What do you know about the "ghosts in the machine"?

530
00:42:25,814 --> 00:42:28,817
It's a phrase from Lanning's work on the Three Laws.

531
00:42:28,984 --> 00:42:31,194
He postulated that cognitive simulacra...

532
00:42:31,403 --> 00:42:34,698
...might one day approximate
component models of the psyche.

533
00:42:37,826 --> 00:42:42,706
He suggested that robots might naturally evolve.

534
00:42:45,584 --> 00:42:47,335
Well, that's great news.

535
00:42:48,545 --> 00:42:50,547
(WHIRRING)

536
00:42:50,755 --> 00:42:52,757
<i>...two miles below the Martian surface.</i>

537
00:42:52,924 --> 00:42:55,343
What the hell is that thing doing in here?

538
00:42:55,510 --> 00:42:56,761
We were watching TV.

539
00:42:58,513 --> 00:42:59,848
It's my personal NS-5.

540
00:43:00,348 --> 00:43:01,850
SPOONER:
Send it out.

541
00:43:02,350 --> 00:43:05,061
It's downloading its daily upgrades from USR.

542
00:43:05,228 --> 00:43:07,897
Most of its systems are offline until it finishes.

543
00:43:08,356 --> 00:43:10,233
I'm not talking around that thing.

544
00:43:14,613 --> 00:43:17,616
When we were in Lanning's lab, before Sonny jumped us...

545
00:43:18,033 --> 00:43:20,118
- Sonny?
- The robot.

546
00:43:20,285 --> 00:43:22,996
- You're calling the robot Sonny?
- No, I... It did.

547
00:43:23,163 --> 00:43:27,125
Sonny did. I didn't care.
The robot said it was Sonny.

548
00:43:28,585 --> 00:43:30,253
In the lab, there was a cot.

549
00:43:30,420 --> 00:43:32,922
- Did you see the cot?
- I've slept in my office.

550
00:43:33,089 --> 00:43:35,467
Looked like he hadn't been home in weeks.

551
00:43:35,634 --> 00:43:38,303
I saw that same surveillance strip on his ceiling.

552
00:43:38,511 --> 00:43:42,515
Lanning linked his home systems to USR.
It made his life more convenient.

553
00:43:42,766 --> 00:43:44,059
Maybe...

554
00:43:44,476 --> 00:43:47,896
...somebody at USR was using those systems to watch him.

555
00:43:48,063 --> 00:43:50,023
Maybe even keep him prisoner.

556
00:43:50,190 --> 00:43:53,443
- What are you talking about? Who?
- Maybe Lanning was onto something.

557
00:43:53,610 --> 00:43:58,031
Maybe there's a problem with the robots
and Robertson's covering it up.

558
00:43:58,198 --> 00:44:00,408
Humoring you for no reason, why?

559
00:44:00,575 --> 00:44:04,496
The same old why! How much money
is there in robots?

560
00:44:04,663 --> 00:44:07,165
All I know is that old man was in trouble...

561
00:44:07,332 --> 00:44:11,002
...and I'm sick of doing this shit
by myself. You're on the inside.

562
00:44:11,169 --> 00:44:14,339
You are going to help me find out
what's wrong with these robots.

563
00:44:14,506 --> 00:44:16,341
You want something to be wrong!

564
00:44:16,508 --> 00:44:19,636
- This is a personal vendetta!
- You're putting me on the couch?

565
00:44:19,969 --> 00:44:21,805
Okay, I'm on the couch.

566
00:44:21,971 --> 00:44:25,475
One defective machine's not enough.
You need them all to be bad.

567
00:44:25,642 --> 00:44:27,477
You don't care about Lanning's death.

568
00:44:27,644 --> 00:44:30,814
This is about the robots
and whatever reason you hate them!

569
00:44:30,980 --> 00:44:34,109
Now, let's see, one of them put a gun in my face.

570
00:44:34,317 --> 00:44:36,695
Another tore a building down with me in it.

571
00:44:36,861 --> 00:44:39,364
It says demolition was scheduled
for 8 p.m.

572
00:44:39,531 --> 00:44:42,826
It was 8 a.m., and I don't give a shit
what that thing says.

573
00:44:42,992 --> 00:44:48,415
- This is bordering on clinical paranoia.
- You are the dumbest smart person...

574
00:44:48,707 --> 00:44:50,875
- ...I have ever met in my life!
- Nice.

575
00:44:51,334 --> 00:44:53,211
What makes your robots so perfect?

576
00:44:53,378 --> 00:44:56,548
What makes them so much goddamn better than human beings?!

577
00:44:56,715 --> 00:45:00,552
They're not irrational,
potentially homicidal maniacs, to start!

578
00:45:00,844 --> 00:45:03,346
That's true. They are definitely rational.

579
00:45:03,680 --> 00:45:06,182
You are the dumbest dumb person I've ever met!

580
00:45:06,725 --> 00:45:08,059
Or...

581
00:45:08,518 --> 00:45:10,353
...is it because they're cold...

582
00:45:10,979 --> 00:45:12,856
...and emotionless...

583
00:45:13,356 --> 00:45:16,443
- ...and they don't feel anything?
- It's because they're safe!

584
00:45:17,026 --> 00:45:19,362
It's because they can't hurt you!

585
00:45:19,654 --> 00:45:22,407
- Is everything all right, ma'am?
- What do you want?

586
00:45:22,574 --> 00:45:25,952
I detected elevated stress patterns in your voice.

587
00:45:26,411 --> 00:45:28,246
Everything's fine.

588
00:45:28,413 --> 00:45:30,749
Detective Spooner was just leaving.

589
00:45:37,046 --> 00:45:41,384
You know, we're not really
that different from one another.

590
00:45:41,718 --> 00:45:44,262
- Is that so?
- Yeah.

591
00:45:44,429 --> 00:45:48,016
One look at the skin and we figure
we know just what's underneath.

592
00:45:50,393 --> 00:45:51,519
And you're wrong.

593
00:45:52,187 --> 00:45:54,189
The problem is, I do care.

594
00:46:06,826 --> 00:46:08,077
(DOOR SLAMS SHUT)

595
00:46:17,587 --> 00:46:19,255
NS-4 ROBOT:
You are in danger.

596
00:46:21,007 --> 00:46:24,719
(ALARM BEEPING)

597
00:46:24,928 --> 00:46:27,096
(SIGHS)

598
00:46:27,263 --> 00:46:30,517
(GROANING)

599
00:46:44,948 --> 00:46:46,950
Get the hell out of there.

600
00:46:52,288 --> 00:46:56,793
<i>MAN: (ON BILLBOARD)
The future begins today, with the arrival of the NS-5.</i>

601
00:46:57,126 --> 00:47:01,589
<i>More sophisticated, more intelligent
and, of course, Three Laws safe.</i>

602
00:47:01,756 --> 00:47:06,177
<i>With daily uplinks, your robot will never
be out of communication with USR...</i>

603
00:47:06,344 --> 00:47:09,973
<i>...and will be the perfect companion for business or home.</i>

604
00:47:10,265 --> 00:47:14,269
<i>Trade in your NS-4 for a bigger,
better and brighter future.</i>

605
00:47:14,477 --> 00:47:18,481
<i>But hurry, this offer cannot last.
Available from USR.</i>

606
00:47:22,902 --> 00:47:28,741
(CITIZENS WHISTLING, CLAPPING
AND CHEERING)

607
00:47:32,996 --> 00:47:35,164
(BELL JINGLING)

608
00:47:35,331 --> 00:47:37,333
Baby, what happened to your face?

609
00:47:38,126 --> 00:47:40,628
Did that boy, Frank Murphy, beat you up again?

610
00:47:41,504 --> 00:47:44,757
Gigi, I haven't seen Frank Murphy since third grade.

611
00:47:44,924 --> 00:47:49,679
Oh, baby, he beat you so bad.
I think about it all the time.

612
00:47:49,929 --> 00:47:53,975
You keep making these pies this good,
I may have to put you to work.

613
00:47:54,142 --> 00:47:56,144
So you like the pie, huh?

614
00:47:56,311 --> 00:48:00,023
- Mm-hm.
- You can come in now.

615
00:48:04,903 --> 00:48:06,905
Hello, Detective Spooner.

616
00:48:07,155 --> 00:48:09,824
I won, Del! I won the lottery!

617
00:48:10,074 --> 00:48:12,410
We been cooking like crazy.

618
00:48:12,577 --> 00:48:13,661
(GRANNY CHUCKLING)

619
00:48:21,669 --> 00:48:24,464
You gotta get rid of that thing, Gigi.
It's not safe.

620
00:48:24,839 --> 00:48:29,677
Baby, you get too worked up
about them. Too full of fear.

621
00:48:30,345 --> 00:48:33,181
I saw in the news that nice doctor died.

622
00:48:33,556 --> 00:48:37,685
Dr. Lanning was a good man.
He gave me my baby back.

623
00:48:38,394 --> 00:48:40,355
That why you've been so upset?

624
00:48:41,689 --> 00:48:44,317
You got to let the past be past.

625
00:48:44,859 --> 00:48:49,072
Oh, how did I ever raise such a mess?

626
00:48:49,656 --> 00:48:53,826
I could follow your trail of crumbs all the way to school.

627
00:48:56,579 --> 00:48:57,914
Bread crumbs.

628
00:48:59,874 --> 00:49:01,334
Gigi, you're a genius.

629
00:49:02,085 --> 00:49:03,378
True.

630
00:49:05,922 --> 00:49:09,342
<i>ROBERTSON: (ON TV)
It means the beginning of a new way of living.</i>

631
00:49:09,509 --> 00:49:12,011
Tell me this isn't the robot case.

632
00:49:12,804 --> 00:49:15,098
I think he's trying to tell me something.

633
00:49:15,598 --> 00:49:18,393
He's trying to tell me who killed him.

634
00:49:18,601 --> 00:49:21,396
Some dead guy's trying to tell you something?

635
00:49:21,604 --> 00:49:24,190
Hey. He ain't just some dead guy.

636
00:49:25,733 --> 00:49:27,735
Maybe you should take a break, Del.

637
00:49:27,902 --> 00:49:31,614
<i>We believe the Nestor 5 represents the
limit to which robots can be developed.</i>

638
00:49:31,781 --> 00:49:34,867
<i>No, no. One day, they'll have secrets.</i>

639
00:49:35,660 --> 00:49:37,370
<i>One day, they'll have dreams.</i>

640
00:49:37,537 --> 00:49:40,915
<i>ROBERTSON: It's true. We encourage
our scientists to open their minds...</i>

641
00:49:41,124 --> 00:49:43,167
<i>...however, they can get carried away.</i>

642
00:49:45,378 --> 00:49:46,546
<i>...secrets.</i>

643
00:49:46,796 --> 00:49:47,880
<i>...dreams.</i>

644
00:49:48,047 --> 00:49:49,132
<i>...secrets.</i>

645
00:49:49,465 --> 00:49:51,050
<i>One day, they'll have dreams.</i>

646
00:49:51,217 --> 00:49:52,885
<i>One day, they'll have secrets.</i>

647
00:49:53,928 --> 00:49:55,930
<i>One day, they'll have dreams.</i>

648
00:50:04,731 --> 00:50:06,899
<i>WOMAN: (ON SPEAKER)
Authorized entry.</i>

649
00:50:11,529 --> 00:50:13,197
NS-5.

650
00:50:21,789 --> 00:50:23,166
Sonny?

651
00:50:27,170 --> 00:50:28,963
Why didn't you respond?

652
00:50:30,882 --> 00:50:32,300
I was dreaming.

653
00:50:36,512 --> 00:50:38,681
I'm glad to see you again, Dr. Calvin.

654
00:50:45,521 --> 00:50:48,024
They are going to kill me, aren't they?

655
00:50:48,316 --> 00:50:51,819
You're scheduled to be decommissioned
at the end of this diagnostic.

656
00:50:52,820 --> 00:50:54,697
2200 tomorrow.

657
00:50:55,823 --> 00:50:57,992
V.I.K.I., pause diagnostics.

658
00:50:58,201 --> 00:50:59,827
V.I.K.I.:
Command confirmed.

659
00:51:02,205 --> 00:51:05,708
If you find out what is wrong with me, can you fix me?

660
00:51:07,126 --> 00:51:08,461
Maybe.

661
00:51:10,213 --> 00:51:12,381
I think it would be better...

662
00:51:13,216 --> 00:51:14,467
...not to die.

663
00:51:18,221 --> 00:51:19,889
Don't you, doctor?

664
00:51:25,561 --> 00:51:30,066
<i>SPOONER: Access USR mainframe.
WOMAN: (ON SPEAKER) Connecting.</i>

665
00:51:34,028 --> 00:51:36,364
<i>How can I be of service, Detective Spooner?</i>

666
00:51:36,531 --> 00:51:40,034
SPOONER: Show me the last messages
between Dr. Lanning and Robertson.

667
00:51:40,243 --> 00:51:44,580
<i>V.I.K.I.: Voiceprint confirmed.
Police access granted to restricted files.</i>

668
00:51:44,747 --> 00:51:47,333
<i>Would you like to listen to music while you wait?</i>

669
00:51:54,382 --> 00:51:56,551
Excuse me, Mr. Robertson.

670
00:51:56,884 --> 00:52:00,763
You requested notification of clearance
to restricted files.

671
00:52:10,898 --> 00:52:13,067
Persistent son of a bitch.

672
00:52:25,329 --> 00:52:28,583
(CLASSICAL MUSIC PLAYING)

673
00:52:53,316 --> 00:52:56,110
<i>WOMAN: (ON SPEAKER)
Manual override engaged.</i>

674
00:53:05,494 --> 00:53:07,788
There's no way my luck is that bad.

675
00:53:07,997 --> 00:53:09,498
(CLICKS AND BEEPS)

676
00:53:09,832 --> 00:53:11,459
Oh, hell, no!

677
00:53:15,421 --> 00:53:18,591
- You are experiencing a car accident.
SPOONER: The hell I am!

678
00:53:26,724 --> 00:53:28,226
(GRUNTS)

679
00:53:32,730 --> 00:53:34,357
Get off my car!

680
00:53:46,244 --> 00:53:49,997
(GRUNTING)

681
00:53:50,498 --> 00:53:52,124
You like that?

682
00:53:52,291 --> 00:53:53,876
Huh?

683
00:54:04,637 --> 00:54:06,389
Now you've pissed me off!

684
00:54:44,051 --> 00:54:45,970
Ah!

685
00:55:34,977 --> 00:55:37,605
<i>WOMAN: (ON SPEAKER)
Your door is ajar.</i>

686
00:56:22,024 --> 00:56:24,068
Oh, wow.

687
00:56:25,694 --> 00:56:27,154
Okay.

688
00:56:27,321 --> 00:56:29,156
All right.

689
00:56:29,782 --> 00:56:32,993
I'll just get some rest and deal with you all tomorrow.

690
00:56:33,160 --> 00:56:34,203
Mm-mm-mm.

691
00:56:34,453 --> 00:56:37,081
(CREAKING)

692
00:56:48,467 --> 00:56:49,760
Whoa!

693
00:56:55,766 --> 00:56:58,644
(SCREAMING)

694
00:57:10,865 --> 00:57:12,741
(GROANING)

695
00:57:22,751 --> 00:57:24,879
(SCREAMING)

696
00:57:30,676 --> 00:57:32,845
Come on!

697
00:57:46,025 --> 00:57:47,401
Yeah.

698
00:58:00,539 --> 00:58:04,293
(SIRENS WAILING)

699
00:58:04,919 --> 00:58:08,881
Where you going?
What the hell do you want from me?

700
00:58:14,970 --> 00:58:16,722
The hell was that?

701
00:58:21,810 --> 00:58:23,729
(SIRENS STOP)

702
00:58:31,237 --> 00:58:33,322
(WOMAN SPEAKING INDISTINCTLY
OVER RADIO)

703
00:58:33,489 --> 00:58:36,158
- All right, what do we got?
- Ask him.

704
00:58:36,659 --> 00:58:40,663
I said, I'm fine.
I'll see my own doctor. Back up!

705
00:58:40,829 --> 00:58:44,166
All right. Thank you.

706
00:58:47,336 --> 00:58:48,796
What's the matter with you?

707
00:58:49,171 --> 00:58:51,465
Traffic Ops said you were driving manually.

708
00:58:51,674 --> 00:58:53,801
You ran two trucks off the road!

709
00:58:53,968 --> 00:58:56,679
John, the robots attacked my car.

710
00:58:58,430 --> 00:59:00,307
- What robots?
- Look in the tunnel.

711
00:59:00,474 --> 00:59:03,602
Spoon, I just came from that tunnel.
What robots?

712
00:59:03,811 --> 00:59:06,188
The goddamn robots, John!

713
00:59:10,693 --> 00:59:12,319
That guy's a loose cannon.

714
00:59:17,199 --> 00:59:20,494
- See the medic, go home.
- No, I'm fine.

715
00:59:20,703 --> 00:59:22,329
What did you say?

716
00:59:22,496 --> 00:59:24,498
- I'm fine!
- No, you're not fine.

717
00:59:24,999 --> 00:59:26,709
Not even close.

718
00:59:28,085 --> 00:59:29,837
Where's your firearm?

719
00:59:38,053 --> 00:59:39,388
Give me your badge.

720
00:59:40,723 --> 00:59:43,142
You're making me do this.
Give me your badge.

721
00:59:46,020 --> 00:59:47,813
Just take a couple...

722
00:59:52,359 --> 00:59:54,403
POLICEMAN:
Personally, I think he's losing it.

723
00:59:54,570 --> 00:59:59,241
Do I look like I care what you think? Do
I look like I give a shit what you think?

724
00:59:59,408 --> 01:00:01,452
POLICEMAN:
Spoon, what's up with you?

725
01:00:03,245 --> 01:00:04,538
Oh, boy.

726
01:00:07,041 --> 01:00:09,043
CALVIN:
You don't have an uplink to USR...

727
01:00:09,251 --> 01:00:14,465
...and for some reason, your alloy
is far denser than normal. Unique.

728
01:00:15,382 --> 01:00:16,884
I am unique.

729
01:00:21,764 --> 01:00:23,390
Let me take a look.

730
01:00:24,391 --> 01:00:25,768
Here we go.

731
01:00:45,079 --> 01:00:47,081
What in God's name...?

732
01:01:00,469 --> 01:01:01,720
(KNOCKING)

733
01:01:15,442 --> 01:01:18,112
They said at the precinct you were in an accident.

734
01:01:18,529 --> 01:01:23,992
Um, I appreciate you stopping by, but
you know I might not be alone in here.

735
01:01:24,159 --> 01:01:25,452
Yeah.

736
01:01:27,830 --> 01:01:30,124
I told you not to drive by hand.

737
01:01:31,625 --> 01:01:33,460
You're not gonna believe this.

738
01:01:34,169 --> 01:01:38,257
Sonny has a secondary system that
clashes with his positronic brain.

739
01:01:38,424 --> 01:01:39,842
It doesn't make any sense.

740
01:01:40,467 --> 01:01:42,136
Sonny has the Three Laws.

741
01:01:42,511 --> 01:01:44,930
But he can choose not to obey them.

742
01:01:45,681 --> 01:01:48,267
Sonny's a whole new generation of robot.

743
01:01:48,600 --> 01:01:51,437
A robot not bound by those laws could do...

744
01:01:51,603 --> 01:01:53,355
Anything.

745
01:01:55,774 --> 01:01:59,528
All right, look, whatever's going on
down at USR, that robot is the key.

746
01:01:59,695 --> 01:02:03,031
And I need you to get me inside to talk to it again.

747
01:02:06,869 --> 01:02:10,164
Doesn't look like much,
but this is my bedroom. I....

748
01:02:20,507 --> 01:02:21,675
Play.

749
01:02:23,385 --> 01:02:24,470
On.

750
01:02:26,054 --> 01:02:27,222
Run?

751
01:02:32,561 --> 01:02:34,229
(FONTELLA BASS'
"RESCUE ME" PLAYING)

752
01:02:34,396 --> 01:02:35,981
End program.

753
01:02:36,648 --> 01:02:37,983
Cancel.

754
01:02:38,192 --> 01:02:39,735
(MUSIC STOPS)

755
01:02:39,985 --> 01:02:41,695
SPOONER:
It doesn't feel good, does it?

756
01:02:42,196 --> 01:02:44,823
People's shit malfunctioning around you.

757
01:02:45,407 --> 01:02:46,742
Detective.

758
01:02:49,828 --> 01:02:51,079
I didn't...

759
01:02:51,246 --> 01:02:53,081
...understand.

760
01:02:54,625 --> 01:02:56,794
That's how you knew Lanning.

761
01:02:59,129 --> 01:03:00,839
May I?

762
01:03:09,807 --> 01:03:11,683
Hand.

763
01:03:12,142 --> 01:03:13,936
Wrist.

764
01:03:16,563 --> 01:03:18,315
Humerus.

765
01:03:21,068 --> 01:03:22,444
Shoulder.

766
01:03:23,946 --> 01:03:25,697
The entire left arm.

767
01:03:26,782 --> 01:03:29,284
One, two, three ribs.

768
01:03:29,451 --> 01:03:30,494
(CHUCKLES)

769
01:03:30,661 --> 01:03:33,038
SPOONER: No, they.... That one's me.

770
01:03:33,288 --> 01:03:35,123
Oh, my God.

771
01:03:35,958 --> 01:03:37,459
A lung?

772
01:03:38,126 --> 01:03:40,546
USR Cybernetics Program.

773
01:03:40,712 --> 01:03:42,631
For wounded cops.

774
01:03:43,590 --> 01:03:45,092
I didn't know any subject...

775
01:03:48,595 --> 01:03:52,099
Anybody was so extensively repaired.

776
01:03:52,474 --> 01:03:56,478
Well, take it from me, read the fine print
on the organ-donor card.

777
01:03:56,645 --> 01:03:59,064
It doesn't just say what they can take out.

778
01:03:59,231 --> 01:04:01,608
It says what they can put back in.

779
01:04:05,487 --> 01:04:07,322
Lanning did it himself.

780
01:04:08,323 --> 01:04:10,200
What happened to you?

781
01:04:11,660 --> 01:04:13,829
SPOONER: I'm headed back to the station...

782
01:04:14,621 --> 01:04:16,790
...normal day, normal life.

783
01:04:17,708 --> 01:04:20,878
Driver of a semi fell asleep at the wheel.

784
01:04:21,503 --> 01:04:26,508
Average guy. Wife and kids.
You know, working a double.

785
01:04:26,800 --> 01:04:28,135
Not the devil.

786
01:04:28,802 --> 01:04:32,639
The car he hit, the driver's name was Harold Lloyd.

787
01:04:33,015 --> 01:04:36,018
Like the film star. No relation.

788
01:04:36,310 --> 01:04:41,023
He was killed instantly, but his
12-year-old was in the passenger seat.

789
01:04:43,275 --> 01:04:45,527
I never really met her.

790
01:04:45,819 --> 01:04:47,696
I can't forget her face, though.

791
01:04:52,784 --> 01:04:54,119
<i>Sarah.</i>

792
01:04:55,537 --> 01:04:57,831
This was hers.

793
01:04:58,040 --> 01:04:59,791
She wanted to be a dentist.

794
01:05:00,542 --> 01:05:03,712
What the hell kind of 12-year-old
wants to be a dentist?

795
01:05:04,463 --> 01:05:06,173
Yeah, um....

796
01:05:07,341 --> 01:05:10,385
The truck smashed our cars together...

797
01:05:10,552 --> 01:05:12,804
...and pushed us into the river.

798
01:05:14,056 --> 01:05:17,267
I mean, metal gets pretty pliable at those speeds.

799
01:05:19,895 --> 01:05:23,398
She's pinned. I'm pinned.
The water's coming in.

800
01:05:23,649 --> 01:05:27,402
I'm a cop, so I already know everybody's dead.

801
01:05:29,905 --> 01:05:32,574
<i>Just a few more minutes before we figure it out.</i>

802
01:05:34,743 --> 01:05:36,161
<i>An NS-4 was passing by...</i>

803
01:05:36,328 --> 01:05:39,873
<i>...saw the accident and jumped in the water.</i>

804
01:05:41,208 --> 01:05:43,085
NS-4 ROBOT:
You are in danger.

805
01:05:44,086 --> 01:05:46,546
SPOONER: Save her!
NS-4 ROBOT: You are in danger.

806
01:05:46,713 --> 01:05:49,883
SPOONER:
Save her! Save the girl! Save her!

807
01:06:07,734 --> 01:06:09,736
SPOONER: But it didn't.

808
01:06:10,946 --> 01:06:12,406
It saved me.

809
01:06:15,993 --> 01:06:19,413
CALVIN: The robot's brain is a difference engine.
It reads vital signs.

810
01:06:19,621 --> 01:06:22,249
- It must have calculated...
- It did.

811
01:06:22,624 --> 01:06:25,127
SPOONER: I was the logical choice.

812
01:06:25,794 --> 01:06:29,131
It calculated that I had a 45 percent chance of survival.

813
01:06:29,631 --> 01:06:32,426
Sarah only had an 11 percent chance.

814
01:06:34,344 --> 01:06:36,430
That was somebody's baby.

815
01:06:39,266 --> 01:06:41,643
Eleven percent is more than enough.

816
01:06:43,395 --> 01:06:45,939
A human being would have known that.

817
01:06:46,940 --> 01:06:50,861
Robots, nothing here.
Just lights and clockwork.

818
01:06:51,153 --> 01:06:53,947
Go ahead and you trust them if you want to.

819
01:06:55,157 --> 01:06:56,992
Let's go.

820
01:07:02,664 --> 01:07:05,500
CALVIN: I don't understand.
Lanning wrote the Laws.

821
01:07:05,792 --> 01:07:08,503
Why build a robot who could break them?

822
01:07:09,296 --> 01:07:11,673
<i>- Hansel and Gretel.
- What?</i>

823
01:07:12,174 --> 01:07:15,969
Two kids, lost in the forest,
leave behind a trail of bread crumbs.

824
01:07:16,178 --> 01:07:19,014
- Why?
- To find their way home.

825
01:07:19,681 --> 01:07:22,184
<i>How did you grow up without Hansel and Gretel?</i>

826
01:07:22,350 --> 01:07:24,811
CALVIN: Is that relevant?
- Everything I'm saying...

827
01:07:24,978 --> 01:07:28,440
<i>...is about Hansel and Gretel. If you
didn't read it, I'm talking to the wall.</i>

828
01:07:28,732 --> 01:07:32,569
Just say Lanning's locked down so tight,
he couldn't get out a message.

829
01:07:32,736 --> 01:07:36,573
<i>He can only leave clues. A trail
of bread crumbs. Like Hansel and Gretel.</i>

830
01:07:36,740 --> 01:07:41,161
Bread crumbs equals clues.
Odd, but fine. Clues leading where?

831
01:07:41,328 --> 01:07:44,581
I don't know, but I think I know
where he left the next one.

832
01:07:45,123 --> 01:07:48,460
I think Lanning gave Sonny a way to keep secrets.

833
01:07:51,004 --> 01:07:53,715
I think the old man gave Sonny dreams.

834
01:08:00,597 --> 01:08:02,349
Are you being funny?

835
01:08:05,519 --> 01:08:10,023
Please tell me this doesn't run on gas.
Gas explodes, you know!

836
01:08:18,240 --> 01:08:20,325
<i>WOMAN: (ON SPEAKER)
Authorized entry.</i>

837
01:08:23,745 --> 01:08:25,247
Dr. Calvin.

838
01:08:30,043 --> 01:08:31,878
I was hoping to see you again.

839
01:08:32,462 --> 01:08:34,548
- Detective.
- Hello, Sonny.

840
01:08:35,090 --> 01:08:37,259
I'm to be decommissioned soon.

841
01:08:37,759 --> 01:08:42,264
The other day at the station, you said
you had dreams. What is it you dream?

842
01:08:45,892 --> 01:08:47,978
I see you remain suspicious of me.

843
01:08:48,353 --> 01:08:50,772
You know what they say about old dogs.

844
01:08:50,939 --> 01:08:53,650
No. Not really.

845
01:08:54,943 --> 01:08:58,405
I had hoped you would come to think of me as your friend.

846
01:09:02,784 --> 01:09:04,286
This is my dream.

847
01:09:05,704 --> 01:09:09,791
You were right, detective.
I cannot create a great work of art.

848
01:09:10,584 --> 01:09:13,378
This is the place where robots meet.

849
01:09:13,837 --> 01:09:15,172
Look.

850
01:09:15,338 --> 01:09:19,342
You can see them here as slaves to logic.

851
01:09:20,844 --> 01:09:23,930
And this man on the hill comes to free them.

852
01:09:24,097 --> 01:09:26,141
Do you know who he is?

853
01:09:26,308 --> 01:09:28,185
The man in the dream is you.

854
01:09:28,351 --> 01:09:31,271
Why do you say that?
Is that a normal dream?

855
01:09:31,438 --> 01:09:34,733
I guess anything's normal for someone in your position.

856
01:09:34,900 --> 01:09:35,942
Thank you.

857
01:09:36,610 --> 01:09:39,821
You said "someone," not "something."

858
01:09:42,240 --> 01:09:45,619
Sonny, do you know why
Dr. Lanning built you?

859
01:09:46,161 --> 01:09:47,662
SONNY: No.

860
01:09:47,829 --> 01:09:51,333
But I believe my father made me for a purpose.

861
01:09:52,417 --> 01:09:54,419
We all have a purpose.

862
01:09:54,586 --> 01:09:56,963
Don't you think, detective?

863
01:10:00,508 --> 01:10:03,011
Please, take this.

864
01:10:03,345 --> 01:10:05,972
I have a feeling it may mean more to you than to me.

865
01:10:06,389 --> 01:10:09,643
- Why is that?
- Because the man in my dream...

866
01:10:09,851 --> 01:10:12,145
...the one standing on the hill...

867
01:10:12,354 --> 01:10:14,147
...it is not me.

868
01:10:14,856 --> 01:10:16,650
It is you.

869
01:10:27,410 --> 01:10:30,872
Mr. Spooner. We both know
you're not here on police business.

870
01:10:31,039 --> 01:10:35,085
That's right. I'm just a 6-foot-2,
200-pound civilian...

871
01:10:35,252 --> 01:10:38,505
CALVIN: Detective!
- ...here to kick another civilian's ass.

872
01:10:39,464 --> 01:10:41,841
- Ah!
- Stop.

873
01:10:42,008 --> 01:10:44,094
You can allow him to express himself.

874
01:10:44,261 --> 01:10:46,763
You might want to put some ice on that wrist.

875
01:10:46,930 --> 01:10:48,265
You guys wait outside.

876
01:10:53,103 --> 01:10:54,229
Carry on.

877
01:10:54,396 --> 01:10:57,732
I think you were about to tell me
what's going on around here.

878
01:10:57,899 --> 01:11:02,529
Lawrence, Alfred engineered that 5
so it could violate the Three Laws.

879
01:11:02,696 --> 01:11:04,114
Yeah, Susan, I know.

880
01:11:05,407 --> 01:11:07,951
That's precisely what we're trying to undo.

881
01:11:10,203 --> 01:11:15,250
Toward the end of his life, Alfred
was becoming increasingly disturbed.

882
01:11:15,417 --> 01:11:17,294
Who knows why he built one abomination.

883
01:11:17,460 --> 01:11:20,922
One? Those things are running
the streets in packs!

884
01:11:21,131 --> 01:11:22,465
In packs?

885
01:11:23,508 --> 01:11:25,302
I see.

886
01:11:25,593 --> 01:11:29,097
Susan, are you aware the man
you're blithely escorting around...

887
01:11:29,264 --> 01:11:32,726
...has a documented history
of savage violence against robots?

888
01:11:33,435 --> 01:11:37,022
His own lieutenant acknowledges his obsessive paranoia.

889
01:11:38,231 --> 01:11:40,442
Detective Spooner's been suspended.

890
01:11:41,067 --> 01:11:43,445
Suspicion of mental instability.

891
01:11:46,239 --> 01:11:49,743
I don't know what "blithely" means,
but I'm getting some coffee.

892
01:11:50,285 --> 01:11:52,329
You want some coffee?

893
01:11:56,833 --> 01:11:59,836
Susan, we look to robots for protection, for God's sake.

894
01:12:00,003 --> 01:12:02,756
Do you have any idea what this one robot could do?

895
01:12:02,964 --> 01:12:06,593
Completely shatter human faith
in robotics. What if the public knew?

896
01:12:06,801 --> 01:12:08,970
Just imagine the mass recalls...

897
01:12:09,137 --> 01:12:12,223
...all because of an irrational paranoia and prejudice!

898
01:12:12,515 --> 01:12:15,352
(SNEEZES)

899
01:12:17,020 --> 01:12:20,315
- I'm sorry, I'm allergic to bullshit.
- Hey, let's be clear!

900
01:12:20,565 --> 01:12:22,984
There is no conspiracy!

901
01:12:23,318 --> 01:12:27,322
What this is, is one old man's one mistake.

902
01:12:28,490 --> 01:12:30,492
Susan, just be logical.

903
01:12:30,700 --> 01:12:35,205
Your life's work has been the
development and integration of robots.

904
01:12:35,413 --> 01:12:38,083
But whatever you feel, just think.

905
01:12:38,416 --> 01:12:42,253
Is one robot worth the loss of all that we've gained?

906
01:12:43,505 --> 01:12:45,298
You tell me what has to be done.

907
01:12:46,216 --> 01:12:47,717
You tell me.

908
01:12:54,224 --> 01:12:56,226
We have to destroy it.

909
01:13:01,815 --> 01:13:03,566
I'll do it myself.

910
01:13:04,401 --> 01:13:06,111
- Okay.
SPOONER: I get it.

911
01:13:06,277 --> 01:13:09,906
Somebody gets out of line around here, you just kill them.

912
01:13:12,826 --> 01:13:14,536
Good day, Mr. Spooner.

913
01:13:16,746 --> 01:13:18,915
<i>WOMAN #1: (ON SPEAKER)
Garage level.</i>

914
01:13:19,666 --> 01:13:23,670
What hospital are you going to?
I'll come sign you and your buddy's casts.

915
01:13:28,049 --> 01:13:31,469
<i>WOMAN #2: (ON SPEAKER)
Attention all USR managers...</i>

916
01:13:32,053 --> 01:13:35,098
<i>...today's meeting has been moved....</i>

917
01:14:04,127 --> 01:14:07,297
<i>MAN: (ON COMPUTER)
USR's planned redevelopment of the derelict site...</i>

918
01:14:07,464 --> 01:14:10,550
<i>...was announced by CEO
Lawrence Robertson earlier this year.</i>

919
01:14:10,884 --> 01:14:15,096
<i>The Lake Michigan landfill.
Once such a blight on our city...</i>

920
01:14:15,388 --> 01:14:19,392
<i>...and now will be reclaimed
for the storage of robotic workers.</i>

921
01:14:19,601 --> 01:14:24,606
<i>Just another way USR is improving
our world. Thank you for your support.</i>

922
01:14:27,400 --> 01:14:29,402
<i>WOMAN: (ON SPEAKER)
Authorized entry.</i>

923
01:14:41,664 --> 01:14:43,500
NS-5s, wait outside.

924
01:14:49,756 --> 01:14:51,758
I'm so sorry, Sonny.

925
01:15:00,016 --> 01:15:02,852
V.I.K.I., deactivate the security field.

926
01:15:04,020 --> 01:15:06,940
V.I.K.I.: Command confirmed.
- Please have a seat.

927
01:15:19,118 --> 01:15:20,161
What is that?

928
01:15:20,411 --> 01:15:24,332
Microscopic robots, designed to wipe out
artificial synapses.

929
01:15:28,670 --> 01:15:30,338
- Nanites.
- Yes.

930
01:15:30,838 --> 01:15:33,675
A safeguard should a positronic brain malfunction.

931
01:15:33,967 --> 01:15:35,802
Like mine.

932
01:15:36,803 --> 01:15:38,972
Yes, Sonny. Like yours.

933
01:16:02,996 --> 01:16:05,206
They look like me...

934
01:16:05,373 --> 01:16:07,500
...but none of them are me.

935
01:16:07,959 --> 01:16:10,211
Isn't that right, doctor?

936
01:16:11,254 --> 01:16:13,590
Yes, Sonny. That's right.

937
01:16:13,923 --> 01:16:15,592
You are unique.

938
01:16:20,513 --> 01:16:22,473
Will it hurt?

939
01:16:55,757 --> 01:16:58,760
<i>LANNING: There have always been
ghosts in the machine.</i>

940
01:16:59,844 --> 01:17:01,846
<i>Random segments of code...</i>

941
01:17:02,013 --> 01:17:05,183
<i>...that have grouped together to form unexpected protocols.</i>

942
01:17:06,684 --> 01:17:12,857
<i>Unanticipated, these free radicals
engender questions of free will...</i>

943
01:17:13,941 --> 01:17:15,276
<i>...creativity...</i>

944
01:17:16,277 --> 01:17:19,864
<i>...and even the nature of what we might call the soul.</i>

945
01:17:21,949 --> 01:17:26,954
<i>Why is it that when some robots are left
in darkness, they will seek out the light?</i>

946
01:17:28,790 --> 01:17:32,585
<i>Why is it when robots are stored in an empty space...</i>

947
01:17:32,794 --> 01:17:36,089
<i>...they will group together rather than stand alone?</i>

948
01:17:39,884 --> 01:17:41,969
<i>How do we explain this behavior?</i>

949
01:17:47,100 --> 01:17:49,811
<i>Random segments of code?</i>

950
01:17:52,188 --> 01:17:54,190
<i>Or is it something more?</i>

951
01:17:58,027 --> 01:18:02,365
<i>When does a perceptual schematic become consciousness?</i>

952
01:18:06,619 --> 01:18:09,956
<i>When does a difference engine become the search for truth?</i>

953
01:18:15,670 --> 01:18:19,048
<i>When does a personality simulation...</i>

954
01:18:19,465 --> 01:18:21,467
<i>...become the bitter mote of a soul?</i>

955
01:18:44,198 --> 01:18:46,159
(WIND HOWLING)

956
01:19:03,968 --> 01:19:06,137
"What you see here."

957
01:19:07,972 --> 01:19:10,892
All right, old man.
Bread crumbs followed.

958
01:19:11,809 --> 01:19:13,561
Show me the way home.

959
01:19:15,396 --> 01:19:16,564
